alternatives.transcript: mister leslie palmer's case mister leslie palmer was a patient in room eleven at our emergency room today mister palmer presented to the emergency department with as a sixty two year old male who came to the ed due to feeling short of breath for the last six months mister palmer stated that he felt sore all over and couldn't participate in any exercise without feeling short of breath or feeling tired in general mister palmer also stated that he had a lower extremity edema bilaterally as well as only feels comfort at rest in the semi fowler position mister palmer his past medical history consists of diabetes hypertension hyperlipidemia and paroxysmal atrial fibrillation his past surgical history includes a stent placed five years ago and a cabg coronary artery bypass graft placed twelve years prior to the visit today mister palmer has no known allergies and takes numerous medications such as atorvastatin clopidogrel furosemide metoprolol succinate lisinopril metformin and warfarin mister palmer lives at home he's married he currently lives with his wife on upon physical exam mister palmer displayed jvd laterally replaced pmi laterally displaced pmi rails pedal edema as well as cardiomegal megalite and pulmonary edema on chest x-ray x-ray mister palmer's ekg consists of normal sinus rhythm at ninety beats per minute mister palmer also had a left bundle branch block as well as met left ventricular hypertrophy voltage criteria he also his lab work displayed elevated troponin as well as bnp with this said mister palmer was diagnosed with ischemic dilated cardiomyopathy his echo also showed this and supported this with the dilated ventricle as well as thinned septum he was admitted to the icu for monitoring and evaluation by interventional cardiology mister palmer's diagnosis warranted vitals every two hours a strict bed rest nursing interventions as well as a low sodium diet kbo clopidogrel warfarin and dobutamine administration as well as an insulin scot sliding scale this concludes mister palmer's case presentation thank you
